			<exercises>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							Which of the following matrices are orthogonally diagonalizable?
							<ol>
								<li><m>\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
								<li><m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -2 \amp 5 \\ -2 \amp \pi \amp 0 \\ 5 \amp 0 \amp -3\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
								<li><m>\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp -4 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 12 \amp 0 \amp 7 \\ 1 \amp -4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 7 \amp 1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>.</li>
							</ol>
							<aside><p> (Source: None) </p></aside>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							<p><xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> makes this something you can check without any calculations.</p>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<p>By <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> a matrix is orthogonally diagonalizable if and only if it is symmetric.  The first and third matrices are not symmetric, but the second one is, so only the second one is orthogonally diagonalizable.</p>
						</solution>
						<answer><p>Only (b).</p></answer>
					</exercise></p>	

