					<p><exercise>
						<statement>
							Suppose that <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are orthogonally diagonalizable, and that <m>AB=BA</m>.  Prove that <m>AB</m> is orthogonally diagonalizable.
							<aside><p>(Source: None)</p></aside>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							<p>Orthogonal diagonalizability is a hard property to work with, but <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> can help.</p>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<p> By <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are symmetric.  Now we calculate: <me>(AB)^t = B^tA^t = BA = AB</me>.  Thus <m>AB</m> is symmetric, so by <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> <m>AB</m> is orthogonally diagonalizable. </p>
						</solution>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise>
						<statement>
							Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m> B = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Show that <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are orthogonally diagonalizable, but <m>AB</m> is not.
							<aside><p>(Source: None)</p></aside>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							<p>Once again, <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> lets us convert this problem into a much easier one.</p>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<p>Both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are symmetric, so by <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" /> they are orthogonally diagonalizable.  We calculate <me>AB = \begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp -2\end{bmatrix}</me>.  We see that <m>AB</m> is not symmetric, so it is not orthogonally diagonalizable (by <xref ref="thm-spectral-thm" />).</p>
						</solution>
					</exercise></p>
